<div class=3D"personalization-container " id=3D"web-application-body-contai=
ner">
<section xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" id=3D"doc_center_content" i=
temprop=3D"content" lang=3D"en" data-language=3D"en" data-bs-spy=3D"scroll"=
 data-bs-target=3D"#nav_scrollspy"><div id=3D"pgtype-topic">
<section itemprop=3D"content"><h1 class=3D"r2023b" itemprop=3D"title conten=
t" id=3D"mw_97092758-d8bf-4f78-bf1d-321bac31d09a">Explore 3-D Labeled Volum=
etric Data with <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Volume Viewer</strong></h1>=
<div class=3D"examples_short_list hidden_ios_android"><div data-pane=3D"met=
adata" class=3D"panel metadata_container panel-default"><div class=3D"panel=
-body metadata_content open_example_div"><button type=3D"button" class=3D"b=
tn companion_btn btn_color_blue btn-block copy_cmd_btn" data-toggle=3D"popo=
ver" data-placement=3D"bottom" data-trigger=3D"hover focus" title=3D"" data=
-html=3D"true" data-content=3D"<code>openExample('images/Explore3DLabeledVo=
lumetricDataWithVolumeViewerExample')</code>" data-original-title=3D"MATLAB=
 Command"><span class=3D"icon-mw-copy"><span class=3D"sr-only">Copy Code</s=
pan></span>&nbsp; Copy Command</button></div></div></div><div itemscope=3D"=
" itemtype=3D"http://www.mathworks.com/help/schema/MathWorksDocPage/Example=
" itemprop=3D"example" class=3D"em_example"><meta itemprop=3D"exampleid" co=
ntent=3D"images-Explore3DLabeledVolumetricDataWithVolumeViewerExample"><met=
a itemprop=3D"exampletitle" content=3D"Explore 3D Labeled Volumetric Data w=
ith Volume Viewer"></div><span id=3D"Explore3DLabeledVolumetricDataWithVolu=
meViewerExample" class=3D"anchor_target"></span><p class=3D"shortdesc">This=
 example shows how to explore 3-D labeled volumetric data using the <strong=
 class=3D"emphasis bold">Volume Viewer</strong> app. Using the app, you can=
 view the labeled volume by itself or view the labels as an overlay on the =
intensity volume. To illustrate, the example loads an intensity volume that=
 shows the human brain with labeled areas that show the location and type o=
f tumors found in the brain.</p><div class=3D"procedure"><h3 class=3D"title=
" id=3D"Explore3DLabeledVolumetricDataWithVolumeViewerExample-1">Load Label=
ed Volume and Intensity Volume</h3><p>Load the MRI intensity data of a huma=
n brain and the labeled volume from MAT files into the workspace. The MRI d=
ata is a modified subset of the BraTS data set [1]. This operation creates =
two variables in the workspace: <code class=3D"literal">vol</code> and <cod=
e class=3D"literal">label</code>.</p><div class=3D"code_responsive -has_cod=
e_copy"><div class=3D"programlisting"><div class=3D"codeinput"><div class=
=3D"btn-group code_actions"> <button type=3D"button" class=3D"btn btn-defau=
lt dropdown-toggle" data-toggle=3D"dropdown" aria-haspopup=3D"true" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false"> <span class=3D"copy_code_popover_target" id=3D"copy_popov=
er_00"><span class=3D"icon-copy" id=3D"copy_popover_00"></span> Get <span c=
lass=3D"caret" id=3D"copy_popover_00"></span></span></button><ul class=3D"d=
ropdown-menu dropdown-menu-right copy_code"><li class=3D"copy_code_block"><=
button id=3D"copyBlock00"><span class=3D"icon-copy"></span> Copy Code Block=
</button></li><li role=3D"separator" aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"divider"=
></li><li class=3D"copy_code_openexample"><p><span class=3D"icon-webinar"><=
/span> Copy openExample Command<br><small>Paste command in MATLAB to downlo=
ad and open example files</small></p><div role=3D"presentation" class=3D"in=
put-group"><input type=3D"text" class=3D"form-control" readonly=3D"" value=
=3D"openExample('images/Explore3DLabeledVolumetricDataWithVolumeViewerExamp=
le')"><span class=3D"input-group-btn"><button class=3D"btn btn_color_blue" =
type=3D"button" id=3D"copyCommand00"><span class=3D"icon-copy"><span class=
=3D"sr-only">Copy</span></span></button></span></div></li></ul></div><pre>d=
atadir =3D fullfile(toolboxdir(<span style=3D"color:#A020F0">"images"</span=
>),<span style=3D"color:#A020F0">"imdata"</span>,<span style=3D"color:#A020=
F0">"BrainMRILabeled"</span>);
load(fullfile(datadir,<span style=3D"color:#A020F0">"images"</span>,<span s=
tyle=3D"color:#A020F0">"vol_001.mat"</span>));
load(fullfile(datadir,<span style=3D"color:#A020F0">"labels"</span>,<span s=
tyle=3D"color:#A020F0">"label_001.mat"</span>));
whos</pre></div></div></div><div class=3D"code_responsive"><div class=3D"pr=
ogramlisting"><div class=3D"codeoutput"><pre>  Name           Size         =
           Bytes  Class     Attributes

  datadir        1x1                       346  string             =20
  label        240x240x155             8928000  uint8              =20
  vol          240x240x155            17856000  uint16             =20
</pre></div></div></div><p>Open the Volume Viewer app. From the MATLAB tool=
strip, open the Apps tab and under Image Processing and Computer Vision, cl=
ick Volume Viewer. You can also open the app using the <code class=3D"liter=
al">volumeViewer</code> command.</p><div class=3D"code_responsive"><pre id=
=3D"d126e10041" class=3D"programlisting">volumeViewer(vol,label)
</pre></div><p>Load the labeled volume into the Volume Viewer app. Click <s=
trong class=3D"emphasis bold">Import Labeled Volume</strong> to open the la=
beled volume. You can load an image in a file name or load a variable from =
the workspace. (If you have volumetric data in a DICOM format that uses mul=
tiple files to represent a volume, you can specify the DICOM folder name.) =
For this example, choose the<strong class=3D"emphasis bold"> Import From Wo=
rkspace</strong> option.</p><div class=3D"informalfigure"><div id=3D"d126e1=
0052" class=3D"mediaobject"><p><img src=3D"https://ww2.mathworks.cn/help/re=
leases/R2023b/examples/images/win64/Explore3DLabeledVolumetricDataWithVolum=
eViewerExample_01.png" height=3D"375" width=3D"684"></p></div></div><p>Sele=
ct the workspace variable associated with the labeled volume data in the <s=
trong class=3D"emphasis bold">Import from Workspace</strong> dialog box and=
 click <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">OK</strong>.</p><div class=3D"inform=
alfigure"><div id=3D"d126e10064" class=3D"mediaobject"><p><img src=3D"https=
://ww2.mathworks.cn/help/releases/R2023b/examples/images/win64/Explore3DLab=
eledVolumetricDataWithVolumeViewerExample_02.png" height=3D"350" width=3D"3=
81"></p></div></div><h3 class=3D"title" id=3D"Explore3DLabeledVolumetricDat=
aWithVolumeViewerExample-2"><strong class=3D"emphasis bold">View Labeled Vo=
lume in Volume Viewer</strong></h3><p>View the labeled volume in the Volume=
 Viewer app. By default, the Volume Viewer displays the data as a labeled v=
olume but you can also view it as slice planes. To explore the labeled volu=
me, zoom in and out on the image using the mouse wheel or a right-click. Yo=
u can also rotate the volume by positioning the cursor in the image window,=
 pressing and holding the mouse, and moving the cursor. You are always zoom=
ing or rotating around the center of the volume. The position of the axes i=
n the <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Orientation Axes</strong> window refl=
ects the spatial orientation of the labeled volume as you rotate it.</p><di=
v class=3D"informalfigure"><div id=3D"d126e10077" class=3D"mediaobject"><p>=
<img src=3D"https://ww2.mathworks.cn/help/releases/R2023b/examples/images/w=
in64/Explore3DLabeledVolumetricDataWithVolumeViewerExample_03.png" height=
=3D"784" width=3D"1201"></p></div></div><p>Refine your view of the labeled =
volume using the <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Rendering Editor</strong> =
part of the Volume Viewer. You can use the <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">=
Rendering Editor</strong> to view certain labels and hide others, change th=
e color, and modify the transparency of the labels. Label 000 is the backgr=
ound and it is typically not visible. When you select the background label,=
 the <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Show Labels</strong> check box is clea=
r, by default. To select all the visible labels at once, select the backgro=
und label and click <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Invert Selection</stron=
g>. To change the color of a label (or all the labels), select the label in=
 the <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Rendering Editor</strong> and specify =
the color in the <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Color</strong> selector. Y=
ou can also control the transparency of the label using the <strong class=
=3D"emphasis bold">Opacity</strong> slider.</p><h3 class=3D"title" id=3D"Ex=
plore3DLabeledVolumetricDataWithVolumeViewerExample-3"><strong class=3D"emp=
hasis bold">Embed Labeled Volume with Intensity Volume</strong></h3><p>In t=
his part of the example, you view the labeled volume and the intensity volu=
me in the Volume Viewer at the same time. Viewing the labeled volume overla=
id on the intensity volume can provide context for the data.</p><p>With the=
 labeled volume already in the Volume Viewer, load the intensity volume int=
o the app. Click <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Import Volume</strong> and=
 choose the <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Import From Workspace</strong> =
option.</p><div class=3D"informalfigure"><div id=3D"d126e10118" class=3D"me=
diaobject"><p><img src=3D"https://ww2.mathworks.cn/help/releases/R2023b/exa=
mples/images/win64/Explore3DLabeledVolumetricDataWithVolumeViewerExample_04=
.png" height=3D"343" width=3D"393"></p></div></div><p>Select the workspace =
variable associated with the intensity volume in the <strong class=3D"empha=
sis bold">Import from Workspace</strong> dialog box and click <strong class=
=3D"emphasis bold">OK</strong>.</p><div class=3D"informalfigure"><div id=3D=
"d126e10130" class=3D"mediaobject"><p><img src=3D"https://ww2.mathworks.cn/=
help/releases/R2023b/examples/images/win64/Explore3DLabeledVolumetricDataWi=
thVolumeViewerExample_05.png" height=3D"350" width=3D"381"></p></div></div>=
<p>The Volume Viewer displays the labeled volume over the intensity volumet=
ric data. By default, the Volume Viewer displays the label data and the int=
ensity data as volumes but you can also view it as slice planes. To explore=
 the labeled and intensity volumes, zoom in and out using the mouse wheel o=
r a right-click. You can also rotate the volumes by positioning the cursor =
in the image window, pressing and holding the mouse, and moving the cursor.=
 To view only the intensity volume, and hide the labeled volume, click <str=
ong class=3D"emphasis bold">View Volume</strong>.</p><div class=3D"informal=
figure"><div id=3D"d126e10139" class=3D"mediaobject"><p><img src=3D"https:/=
/ww2.mathworks.cn/help/releases/R2023b/examples/images/win64/Explore3DLabel=
edVolumetricDataWithVolumeViewerExample_06.png" height=3D"791" width=3D"120=
1"></p></div></div><p>Refine your view of the labeled volume and the intens=
ity volume using options in the <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Rendering E=
ditor</strong>. To only view the labeled volume, and hide the intensity vol=
ume, clear the <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Embed Labels in Volume</stro=
ng> check box. In the <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Labels</strong> area =
of the <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Rendering Editor</strong>, you can s=
elect any of the labels and change its color or transparency. Label 000 is =
the background. By default, the background is set to black and is not visib=
le. The <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Show Labels</strong> check box is c=
lear. To select all the labels, click on the background and then click <str=
ong class=3D"emphasis bold">Invert Selection</strong>. If the intensity vol=
ume is visible, you can modify the threshold value and transparency using t=
he sliders in the <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Volume</strong> area of t=
he <strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Rendering Editor</strong>.</p><div class=
=3D"informalfigure"><div id=3D"d126e10170" class=3D"mediaobject"><p><img sr=
c=3D"https://ww2.mathworks.cn/help/releases/R2023b/examples/images/win64/Ex=
plore3DLabeledVolumetricDataWithVolumeViewerExample_07.png" height=3D"798" =
width=3D"1349"></p></div></div><h3 class=3D"title" id=3D"Explore3DLabeledVo=
lumetricDataWithVolumeViewerExample-4">References</h3><p>[1] Medical Segmen=
tation Decathlon. "Brain Tumours." Tasks. Accessed May 10, 2018. <a href=3D=
"http://medicaldecathlon.com/" target=3D"_blank">http://medicaldecathlon.co=
m/.</a></p><p>The BraTS data set is provided by Medical Segmentation Decath=
lon under the CC-BY-SA 4.0 license. All warranties and representations are =
disclaimed. See the license for details. MathWorks=C2=AE has modified the s=
ubset of data used in this example. This example uses the MRI data of one s=
can from the original data set, saved to a MAT file.</p></div>
